title: Updated chrome.d.ts and chrome-app.d.ts to latest version (Chrome 45)
body:
Both [Chrome Extensions](https://developer.chrome.com/extensions/api_index) and [Chrome Apps](https://developer.chrome.com/apps/api_index) APIs updated to latest version (Chrome 45).

They weren't upated in  a long time so lots of modules added. Easier to check which through commits.

_Object_ and _any_ are only used when truly needed. For that explicit types were created for almost everything. Chrome API also uses a lot of properties of _"type X or Y"_ which is a tipical use case for union types.

I've added all missing deprecated functions and properties. They're document, working and might still be in use by someone. It seems to make sense to maintain then until they're completely removed from Chrome API itself.

**Discuss possible improvements on file structure:**

I would like to have some discussion on whether or not to leverage this pull request and make some changes on current file structure.

Although Chrome Plataform API documentation is physically divided into [Extensions](https://developer.chrome.com/extensions/api_index) and [Apps](https://developer.chrome.com/apps/api_index) in reality they are one and only one API with common modules and specific modules to each type of application as it can be visualized [here](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1NGiKEEM6lrAzpt97WuLhWkUgsbXm27_1QerK_hM8y3M/edit#gid=0).

Right now, whoever is developing a Chrome App is referencing not only _chrome-app.d.ts_ but also _chrome.d.ts_ indirectly which is not only wrong (because it exposes modules not available to use) but also leads to a significant increase in file size with code which will never be referenced.

In my opinion a structure like this is would be more appropriate:
- _chrome-api-common.d.ts_
- _chrome-api-extension.d.ts_ - with reference to _chrome-api-common.d.ts_
- _chrome-api-app.d.ts_ - with reference to _chrome-api-common.d.ts_

What's your take on this?

@vvakame @matthewkimber @otiai10 @AdamLay @mzsm you guys have your handles on both definitions so, any input from you would be great :) Thanks

title: Updated for version jq cookie v1.4.1, added jsdoc documentation
body:
The proposed pull request updates the definitions to conform to jquery.cookie version 1.4.1. Since this library is deprecated and moved [here](https://github.com/js-cookie/js-cookie), this should be one of the last pull requests for jquery.cookie. Even though jquery.cookie was deprecated in favour of a jquery-less version, it's still beneficial for DefinitelyTyped to have the most up to date definitions of it, since it is still heavily used. 

The only required addition was for the defaults property, which allows users to set defaults for cookie options.  jsdoc documentation was also added for all properties and methods.  This enables intellisense for editors that support. The jsdoc documentation uses snippets of documentation from the official jquery.cookie github repo as much as possible.

The test file was also updated to test the defaults property.

title: Jasmine: optional expectationFailOutput parameter added to matchers
body:
Currently in our project we don't have an ability to create custom matchers, nor as resources to maintain them.
As well as for some test cases there's not way to use something more that `toBeTruthy()` , or `toBeFalsy()`
That's why it's really important for us to have a way to get any information about reason of failed expectation in test.

Jasmine out-of-the-box is supporting those optional prams, but since we are using TS and your version of jsamine.d.ts - we need to have those optional prams to be added in matchers methods signatures.

In the proposed request I added an optional expectationFailOutput parameter to matchers for ability to track expectation fail reason in output message.

I've added and tested those params passing only to matchers that are actually passing those params to the output.

`npm test` is passing 100%

Reference links to jasmine's `.because(<message>)` discussion:

https://github.com/adobe/brackets/issues/2752

https://github.com/jasmine/jasmine/issues/641#issuecomment-54736801

Please consider this code-change - that would really help us. Thank you.

title: ui-grid: fixed reference to the IGridRow type to refer to uiGrid.IGridRow within ui-grid plugins
body:
Some of the plugins for ui-grid define an `IGridRow` interface to extend the possible options on the `row` object.  The main `IGridRow` interface extends all of the plugins' `IGridRow` interfaces so that you always get the best autocompletion.  But within the plugin modules, referring to the un-qualified `IGridRow` ends up resolving to the inner interface, with only a couple of options.  Using these plugin methods can therefore cause errors when trying to use other (non-plugin) fields on the `row` object.

I have qualified references to `IGridRow` within the plugin modules so the correct `IGridRow` (`uiGrid.IGridRow`) is used.

title: slickgrid: some fixes
body:
- Added `DataProvider.getItemMetadata` which returns new interface `RowMetadata` (https://github.com/mleibman/SlickGrid/wiki/Providing-data-to-the-grid#item-metadata)
- `GroupRowMetadata` and `TotalsRowMetadata` were deleted, new ``RowMetadata` is used instead of them
- Removed `R` type argument from `Group<T,R>` and `GroupTotals<T,R>`. First of all `R` and `T` should be swapped: `R` is a type of `value` and `T` is a type of `rows`. Also `R` is usually unknown and `any` is used. This is inconvenient. So I think removing `R` is the best way.
- All properties of `GroupingOptions` are optional.
